10
00:00:26,835 --> 00:00:28,779
Hi, I'm James Benson.

11
00:00:29,079 --> 00:00:30,982
I worked in AAA for five minutes on Fable,

12
00:00:31,904 --> 00:00:33,266
and then the canceled boy simulator.

13
00:00:34,047 --> 00:00:35,389
Then I made Ori and the Blind Forest,

14
00:00:36,351 --> 00:00:39,756
and Firewatch, and now I'm making In the Valley of Gods.

15
00:00:43,457 --> 00:00:48,221
I'm going to talk specifically about some Unity system stuff, but the gist is all sort

16
00:00:48,261 --> 00:00:48,981
of broadly applicable.

17
00:00:49,582 --> 00:00:54,685
So tip number one, avoiding state machines and trying to keep your animation sets within

18
00:00:54,725 --> 00:00:55,406
a single blend tree.

19
00:00:55,926 --> 00:01:00,389
So the problem with state machines basically is that they give you these kind of binary

20
00:01:00,469 --> 00:01:02,831
possibility states where you're either standing or you're crouched.

21
00:01:03,291 --> 00:01:05,233
And this isn't just a visual problem, it's a controls one.

22
00:01:06,694 --> 00:01:07,614
Why are blend trees better?

23
00:01:08,395 --> 00:01:10,756
So you can exist indefinitely in between two states.

24
00:01:11,456 --> 00:01:13,757
You can transition non-linearly by driving floats.

25
00:01:14,657 --> 00:01:16,438
Mechanin by default, when you go in between states,

26
00:01:16,518 --> 00:01:17,818
you can only do linear stuff.

27
00:01:17,998 --> 00:01:18,799
It's completely hard-coded.

28
00:01:18,819 --> 00:01:19,519
There's no way around it.

29
00:01:20,439 --> 00:01:23,300
Most importantly, they synchronize the footfalls

30
00:01:24,081 --> 00:01:25,681
and they'll scale time so that everything

31
00:01:25,761 --> 00:01:27,282
is seamlessly in sync.

32
00:01:28,242 --> 00:01:29,343
So that's sort of the basics.

33
00:01:30,824 --> 00:01:32,545
Using these bits of knowledge,

34
00:01:32,885 --> 00:01:35,506
you can replace almost all of your locomotion transitions

35
00:01:35,786 --> 00:01:37,347
with dynamically controlled blends.

36
00:01:37,747 --> 00:01:39,348
So here, when we hit the ground,

37
00:01:40,169 --> 00:01:41,870
we're blending into the crouch movement state

38
00:01:42,150 --> 00:01:44,271
that we used for the previous little GIF.

39
00:01:44,791 --> 00:01:47,853
And we can also define how far you're going to blend

40
00:01:47,953 --> 00:01:48,993
into that crouch movement

41
00:01:49,654 --> 00:01:51,635
by how fast you were going when you hit the ground.

42
00:01:52,075 --> 00:01:54,256
So you can actually get a much more dynamic thing

43
00:01:54,296 --> 00:01:56,037
than you would have just by authoring a single clip.

44
00:01:57,265 --> 00:01:59,626
Think of your blend tree like a flowchart asking a series of

45
00:02:00,526 --> 00:02:02,047
progressively more specific questions.

46
00:02:02,427 --> 00:02:04,348
So here, we're also asking how far away are

47
00:02:04,388 --> 00:02:04,988
you from the ground?

48
00:02:05,348 --> 00:02:08,529
And because the answer is not very far, rather than throwing

49
00:02:08,569 --> 00:02:10,450
you into a new state with a big falling loop and your

50
00:02:10,470 --> 00:02:14,031
arms in the air, we just put you into a slow falling walk

51
00:02:14,051 --> 00:02:16,572
where you have one foot out to catch you when you fall, and

52
00:02:16,592 --> 00:02:17,632
then we do the little crouch bounce.

53
00:02:18,112 --> 00:02:20,653
And all in the same blend tree, it keeps you in the same

54
00:02:20,693 --> 00:02:22,313
foot phases, and it's a seamless thing.

55
00:02:23,982 --> 00:02:26,445
If the ground's further, you can go into more traditional falling loops,

56
00:02:26,505 --> 00:02:28,308
and if it's really far, you can do these kind of

57
00:02:28,688 --> 00:02:31,011
I'm going to die when I hit the ground animations.

58
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:33,355
And again, when you do hit the ground,

59
00:02:33,395 --> 00:02:35,377
you know that the feet are going to perfectly be in phase

60
00:02:35,397 --> 00:02:36,539
and it's all going to be nice and seamless.

61
00:02:38,836 --> 00:02:42,020
By putting your time into variations on your loops,

62
00:02:42,060 --> 00:02:44,102
for different directions, accelerations, etc.

63
00:02:44,443 --> 00:02:46,986
You can skip a lot of individual clip authoring and management.

64
00:02:47,547 --> 00:02:51,472
And you'll also find that because you've made so many movement cycles,

65
00:02:51,792 --> 00:02:57,019
you'll just naturally create much broader possibilities for movement for the character.

66
00:02:58,224 --> 00:03:01,728
So tip number two, build multiple layers of dynamics

67
00:03:01,808 --> 00:03:02,869
into your idle behaviors.

68
00:03:03,570 --> 00:03:05,491
So keeping an NPC alive is really hard.

69
00:03:06,933 --> 00:03:08,915
Baking a character's awareness of the environment

70
00:03:09,275 --> 00:03:11,698
into the clips, it works very, very well

71
00:03:11,738 --> 00:03:12,659
in a game like World of Warcraft.

72
00:03:13,119 --> 00:03:16,242
But if you need your NPC to be able to dynamically

73
00:03:16,282 --> 00:03:19,485
direct their attention, like say into the player's eyes

74
00:03:19,525 --> 00:03:21,247
in a first person game, you're gonna have to have

75
00:03:21,307 --> 00:03:22,108
some kind of dynamics.

76
00:03:23,301 --> 00:03:26,610
However, if you build your look at stuff as like a single IK chain,

77
00:03:27,011 --> 00:03:28,175
it's going to be very rigid.

78
00:03:28,195 --> 00:03:29,840
There's going to be no overshoot or overlap.

79
00:03:31,279 --> 00:03:36,461
So if instead you split your character's attention into say the eyes, the head, the chest, the equipment they're using,

80
00:03:37,142 --> 00:03:41,003
even if you want all those things pointed in one direction, they're going to get there with different timings.

81
00:03:41,624 --> 00:03:45,866
And even better, you can point them in different places.

82
00:03:46,066 --> 00:03:49,307
So for example, they have their torch on an interesting thing in the environment,

83
00:03:49,947 --> 00:03:53,309
and then they dynamically look back to you with their head and eyes to sort of signal,

84
00:03:53,589 --> 00:03:54,870
look at this interesting thing I'm pointing at.

85
00:03:56,538 --> 00:04:00,559
Combined with locomotion, you can create interesting behaviors like dynamically looking over their

86
00:04:00,579 --> 00:04:05,240
shoulder when they're walking backwards, or tracking the path that they're moving along

87
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:08,420
to give a sense that the character has some kind of forethought.

88
00:04:09,821 --> 00:04:13,941
Those sort of systems work nicely with full-body IK, terrain kind of stuff, and you just generally

89
00:04:14,001 --> 00:04:18,582
build up a sense that the character is animated within the space in the game and not like

90
00:04:18,902 --> 00:04:20,983
a series of clips in Maya or 3ds Max.

91
00:04:23,072 --> 00:04:25,373
My next tip is facial capture.

92
00:04:26,094 --> 00:04:27,734
This is mostly a thing for small teams,

93
00:04:27,774 --> 00:04:30,936
but my assumption until relatively recently

94
00:04:30,976 --> 00:04:36,358
had been that face cap stuff was gated by enormous budgets

95
00:04:36,438 --> 00:04:37,159
and team sizes.

96
00:04:37,919 --> 00:04:39,620
And it turns out that's just not really the case.

97
00:04:40,760 --> 00:04:44,522
The software and hardware can be gone for a few thousand

98
00:04:44,542 --> 00:04:47,163
dollars, and largely it's the same kind of stuff

99
00:04:47,183 --> 00:04:48,084
that big teams are using.

100
00:04:48,844 --> 00:04:49,744
It's more expensive just like.

101
00:04:50,565 --> 00:04:51,626
getting lots of people to crunch the data.

102
00:04:52,146 --> 00:04:56,229
But I think that it's not something that's super commonly

103
00:04:56,289 --> 00:04:58,410
thought of in small teams as a feasible option.

104
00:05:00,392 --> 00:05:01,973
We've got two animators now at Camposanto,

105
00:05:01,993 --> 00:05:05,235
but even when it was just me and I was doing these initial tests,

106
00:05:05,395 --> 00:05:07,576
it still seemed like a very feasible thing in the pipeline

107
00:05:07,617 --> 00:05:10,058
in terms of the time it takes and so on and so forth.

108
00:05:10,799 --> 00:05:12,240
So those are all my tips and tricks.

109
00:05:12,440 --> 00:05:13,460
If you didn't like any of them,

110
00:05:14,101 --> 00:05:15,762
hopefully you'll like Jalil Sadul's tips.

111
00:05:19,552 --> 00:05:20,533
No, we're good, we're good, we're good.

112
00:05:22,053 --> 00:05:27,316
Hi, my name is Jadul Sadul, and I am the CEO and co-founder

113
00:05:27,436 --> 00:05:28,537
of Stimulant Studios.

114
00:05:29,237 --> 00:05:32,138
It would be presumptuous of me to tell you how to build a

115
00:05:32,179 --> 00:05:33,059
successful company.

116
00:05:33,079 --> 00:05:35,120
I've only been doing this for three years, and I have a

117
00:05:35,160 --> 00:05:37,721
feeling I need 10 more to really get the big picture.

118
00:05:38,482 --> 00:05:41,643
And it's even more ridiculous to be doing this in five minutes, but here we go.

119
00:05:42,343 --> 00:05:46,725
Most people ask how long since we've opened Stimulant Studios, and usually I say three

120
00:05:46,805 --> 00:05:50,266
years, but in reality it's taken over 14 years, my whole career.

121
00:05:51,126 --> 00:05:52,767
A good reputation is crucial.

122
00:05:53,287 --> 00:05:57,429
Someday if you want to stand on your own in this industry, like running a studio, a strong

123
00:05:57,489 --> 00:06:00,910
network and a good rep will be extremely, extremely valuable.

124
00:06:01,490 --> 00:06:04,551
It's a very small industry where everyone knows everyone.

125
00:06:04,872 --> 00:06:05,832
How do you keep a good rep?

126
00:06:06,532 --> 00:06:08,638
You work hard. This is Lee, our Community Manager.

127
00:06:10,137 --> 00:06:14,041
Focus on the achievable dream, not the blue sky dream.

128
00:06:14,301 --> 00:06:17,143
Each step you take, make it your best step forward.

129
00:06:17,583 --> 00:06:19,445
If you find yourself wanting status,

130
00:06:19,565 --> 00:06:21,006
then you are doing it wrong.

131
00:06:21,387 --> 00:06:23,288
The title of supervisor or director

132
00:06:23,508 --> 00:06:25,290
will find you when you are ready.

133
00:06:25,890 --> 00:06:27,852
You want to be remembered as a hard worker.

134
00:06:28,272 --> 00:06:30,334
If you're given a C-shot, don't complain.

135
00:06:31,015 --> 00:06:32,036
Just do the best you can.

136
00:06:32,316 --> 00:06:34,778
You will get noticed if you put your heart and soul into it,

137
00:06:34,798 --> 00:06:37,080
and it might be something that your colleagues never forget.

138
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:42,346
Keep in mind, the best animators out there can turn C shots into A shots.

139
00:06:42,626 --> 00:06:44,909
Now, that's a skill that will get you noticed.

140
00:06:45,750 --> 00:06:47,392
Be remembered as someone reliable.

141
00:06:48,473 --> 00:06:48,673
Nope.

142
00:06:49,694 --> 00:06:49,955
Wrong.

143
00:06:52,738 --> 00:06:53,139
I got it.

144
00:06:53,159 --> 00:06:54,000
There we go.

145
00:06:55,987 --> 00:06:58,867
Da da da, yeah, be even harder.

146
00:06:58,927 --> 00:07:00,348
It's difficult to get your first job,

147
00:07:00,368 --> 00:07:02,308
but it's even harder to keep a job.

148
00:07:02,528 --> 00:07:04,008
Make yourself invaluable to your team.

149
00:07:04,249 --> 00:07:06,369
If you are new to the team, your chances are limited.

150
00:07:07,029 --> 00:07:09,110
Yes, most supervisors play favorites.

151
00:07:09,310 --> 00:07:11,850
Therefore, work towards getting yourself noticed.

152
00:07:12,030 --> 00:07:14,131
We apply the same philosophy at St. Moyer Studios.

153
00:07:14,251 --> 00:07:16,071
If we work hard for our clients,

154
00:07:16,491 --> 00:07:17,572
they will always remember us

155
00:07:17,632 --> 00:07:19,512
and point others in our direction.

156
00:07:20,952 --> 00:07:23,633
Integrity is a huge part of building a strong team.

157
00:07:23,793 --> 00:07:24,753
Be honest.

158
00:07:25,703 --> 00:07:27,986
With your clients, it's better for your brand

159
00:07:28,126 --> 00:07:31,009
if you don't take a job, then take the job and do it badly.

160
00:07:31,169 --> 00:07:33,991
Treat your team and clients like they are a big,

161
00:07:34,232 --> 00:07:34,972
happy family.

162
00:07:35,433 --> 00:07:37,515
There will be ups and downs, but in the end,

163
00:07:37,715 --> 00:07:39,797
the product, as well as the process,

164
00:07:39,817 --> 00:07:41,018
will represent your brand.

165
00:07:42,139 --> 00:07:43,741
Don't just partner with your best friends.

166
00:07:43,861 --> 00:07:46,683
Partner with people who are as hardworking as you are.

167
00:07:46,944 --> 00:07:48,705
Leaving your big ego at the door

168
00:07:48,945 --> 00:07:50,667
is the first thing you do in a partnership.

169
00:07:51,636 --> 00:07:54,819
Know whether to trust your instincts or not trust it.

170
00:07:55,099 --> 00:07:57,180
Use a good 10 years of your career as a guide.

171
00:07:57,661 --> 00:08:00,363
Study decisions you've made and where they've led you.

172
00:08:00,943 --> 00:08:03,345
But also do the same for your leadership team.

173
00:08:03,405 --> 00:08:05,567
Sometimes you have to trust in your business partner's

174
00:08:05,607 --> 00:08:06,948
decision even if you disagree.

175
00:08:07,788 --> 00:08:12,190
If a member of your leadership team makes the wrong call, fix it, learn from it, and

176
00:08:12,250 --> 00:08:13,010
move forward.

177
00:08:13,410 --> 00:08:15,491
Easier said than done, but it works.

178
00:08:16,331 --> 00:08:18,672
Animators can be a bunch of drama queens.

179
00:08:18,872 --> 00:08:20,633
I know, I'm a bigger one myself.

180
00:08:21,213 --> 00:08:22,313
I speak their language.

181
00:08:22,533 --> 00:08:27,175
Happily walking around the studio and bothering everyone means your shot is going really well.

182
00:08:27,675 --> 00:08:31,821
Putting your headphones and hoodie on means your animation is not looking so good.

183
00:08:32,261 --> 00:08:34,745
The trick is knowing how and when to help them.

184
00:08:34,865 --> 00:08:36,808
Sometimes you just need to let them be.

185
00:08:37,048 --> 00:08:40,292
Other times, jump in or that grumpiness will spread like the plague.

186
00:08:40,873 --> 00:08:42,536
My point is, know your team well.

187
00:08:43,730 --> 00:08:45,592
Without respect, it all falls apart.

188
00:08:45,892 --> 00:08:48,355
Too many companies promote based on seniority.

189
00:08:48,675 --> 00:08:49,696
It's a touchy subject.

190
00:08:50,196 --> 00:08:53,259
You want to be respectful and promote your senior employees,

191
00:08:53,459 --> 00:08:56,322
but how many of you have worked under supervisors

192
00:08:56,362 --> 00:08:57,763
you just didn't believe in?

193
00:08:58,604 --> 00:09:00,606
Promoting someone only because of seniority

194
00:09:00,666 --> 00:09:03,369
will disrupt the team and put a needed pressure

195
00:09:03,429 --> 00:09:04,029
on that person.

196
00:09:04,229 --> 00:09:07,172
Promote based on merit, and respect will follow.

197
00:09:08,688 --> 00:09:10,952
Three years ago, we all took a big pay cut.

198
00:09:11,272 --> 00:09:13,616
Luckily, being in Florida, we were able to survive.

199
00:09:14,076 --> 00:09:16,300
But when your studio finds stability,

200
00:09:16,400 --> 00:09:20,085
make sure you re-evaluate everyone who made sacrifices

201
00:09:20,646 --> 00:09:23,410
at the very beginning, or you will lose the same people

202
00:09:23,530 --> 00:09:25,232
who helped build your company.

203
00:09:26,430 --> 00:09:27,792
Have a strong philosophy.

204
00:09:28,172 --> 00:09:31,135
At Stimulo Studios, we believe in never being scared to fail.

205
00:09:31,155 --> 00:09:33,177
Arnold said it, I live by it.

206
00:09:33,837 --> 00:09:36,260
In the past, I only had my family to worry about.

207
00:09:36,500 --> 00:09:38,782
Now we have 40 people and their families.

208
00:09:39,402 --> 00:09:41,324
As a small studio, we have to take risks,

209
00:09:41,464 --> 00:09:43,326
but they have to be calculated risks.

210
00:09:44,007 --> 00:09:46,848
Make sure your leadership team understands your company's philosophy.

211
00:09:47,148 --> 00:09:48,928
If they do, everyone else will.

212
00:09:49,489 --> 00:09:53,850
If I tell you that high quality of work and a family-oriented company is our philosophy,

213
00:09:53,910 --> 00:09:56,011
you'll say that that's everyone else's motto.

214
00:09:56,051 --> 00:09:58,952
But before making any decision, we ask ourselves,

215
00:09:59,512 --> 00:10:02,133
can we produce the quality of work that represents us?

216
00:10:02,573 --> 00:10:04,434
And can we also do it?

217
00:10:05,074 --> 00:10:07,856
Can our team also do it within the deadline?

218
00:10:08,377 --> 00:10:10,879
We don't take a job if it's going to hurt our team

219
00:10:10,939 --> 00:10:12,320
with a lot of overtime.

220
00:10:12,700 --> 00:10:14,301
Well, if you give me $10 million to risk

221
00:10:14,361 --> 00:10:15,903
in Pong in a week, maybe I'd take it.

222
00:10:16,663 --> 00:10:18,425
In the end, our team's well-being

223
00:10:18,465 --> 00:10:20,887
and the quality of work we produce is our brand.

224
00:10:21,247 --> 00:10:21,887
Thank you very much.

225
00:10:22,068 --> 00:10:23,929
And next, we have the lovely Al Mudena.

226
00:10:27,995 --> 00:10:29,815
Okay, we're okay.

227
00:10:29,875 --> 00:10:31,576
Hello, my name is Almudena Soria,

228
00:10:31,716 --> 00:10:32,797
and I work at Naughty Dog.

229
00:10:33,657 --> 00:10:35,898
Today, I want to give some tips about motion capture,

230
00:10:36,498 --> 00:10:38,299
starting with what to do before the shoot.

231
00:10:39,460 --> 00:10:41,861
Often, motion capture sessions are done externally.

232
00:10:42,461 --> 00:10:44,442
We pay for space, actors, data,

233
00:10:44,842 --> 00:10:46,883
so it is very important to plan ahead of time.

234
00:10:47,683 --> 00:10:50,064
Before shooting, you should have a very clear idea

235
00:10:50,204 --> 00:10:51,965
of what you want to capture and how.

236
00:10:52,585 --> 00:10:55,146
This doesn't mean you can't experiment in the stage,

237
00:10:55,466 --> 00:10:57,307
but the bigger decisions should happen in advance.

238
00:10:58,365 --> 00:11:02,531
It is important that you talk to designers, game and creative directors to discuss how

239
00:11:02,551 --> 00:11:06,495
the performances would be, what speeds and height are required, and what is the tone

240
00:11:06,515 --> 00:11:07,016
of the scenes.

241
00:11:08,418 --> 00:11:11,602
Before you shoot, preview the scenes and implement them in the game.

242
00:11:12,042 --> 00:11:14,285
These will answer a lot of questions before the capture.

243
00:11:14,906 --> 00:11:17,349
The more accurate the previews, the better the capture would be.

244
00:11:18,639 --> 00:11:21,040
Once you know what you want to capture, create a shot list.

245
00:11:21,500 --> 00:11:23,802
Have different fields for all the information you need.

246
00:11:24,242 --> 00:11:26,903
Name, description on the move, characters, props.

247
00:11:27,364 --> 00:11:29,945
Try to keep all the information in one place.

248
00:11:30,646 --> 00:11:32,207
Also, try to organize the shots

249
00:11:32,427 --> 00:11:34,168
so you don't have to jump between them.

250
00:11:35,348 --> 00:11:36,569
Use a good naming convention

