00:11:36,789 --> 00:11:38,210
so you know what you are capturing

252
00:11:38,270 --> 00:11:39,331
by just looking at the name.

253
00:11:40,823 --> 00:11:42,784
Have in mind the actor's endurance.

254
00:11:43,264 --> 00:11:45,905
Don't have them doing a crouch move set for five hours

255
00:11:46,425 --> 00:11:48,026
or a sprint right after lunch.

256
00:11:48,686 --> 00:11:49,386
So mix it up.

257
00:11:49,846 --> 00:11:51,767
Not only will it help the actor's well-being,

258
00:11:52,007 --> 00:11:53,007
but also their performance.

259
00:11:54,108 --> 00:11:56,829
When shots require a build, try to sort this in order

260
00:11:57,029 --> 00:11:58,610
so you don't have to take those builds down

261
00:11:58,770 --> 00:12:00,630
if you're going to leave them later.

262
00:12:02,091 --> 00:12:04,352
My next tips are related to the day of the shoot.

263
00:12:05,512 --> 00:12:06,713
We work in empty spaces,

