266
00:12:10,638 --> 00:12:12,800
So take references with you to show them.

267
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:14,741
Things like footage on the game,

268
00:12:15,082 --> 00:12:17,204
concept of the characters, environments,

269
00:12:17,364 --> 00:12:19,125
script of the scenes, and previous.

270
00:12:20,355 --> 00:12:23,975
When giving directions, start by describing the context

271
00:12:24,195 --> 00:12:26,536
and what the situation is and let them act.

272
00:12:27,336 --> 00:12:29,436
While reading this book, directing actors

273
00:12:29,476 --> 00:12:31,437
have learned that if it doesn't work

274
00:12:31,877 --> 00:12:35,117
and it's absolutely necessary to give some more details,

275
00:12:35,397 --> 00:12:37,138
use verbs, not adjectives.

276
00:12:37,778 --> 00:12:41,198
For example, don't say something like, act more nervous.

277
00:12:42,159 --> 00:12:44,239
Instead, you could say, move faster,

278
00:12:44,739 --> 00:12:47,040
try to breathe heavily, fidget with your hands.

279
00:12:48,029 --> 00:12:53,013
I want to emphasize though that it's better to let them act instead of giving such specific

280
00:12:53,073 --> 00:12:53,554
directions.

281
00:12:54,695 --> 00:12:56,636
Also, listen to what the actors have to say.

282
00:12:57,117 --> 00:12:59,919
All the time they come up with ideas that are very, very valuable.

283
00:13:01,401 --> 00:13:06,125
Have someone that is not directing the shoot taking notes, so when the data is delivered

284
00:13:06,305 --> 00:13:09,848
you don't have to look through all of it to know what you like in the first place.

285
00:13:11,385 --> 00:13:13,966
When capturing gameplay, there are specific requirements.

286
00:13:14,166 --> 00:13:15,966
These are speed, movement trajectories,

287
00:13:16,046 --> 00:13:17,087
beginning and end poses.

288
00:13:17,687 --> 00:13:20,048
These restrictions can make the performances stiff

289
00:13:20,168 --> 00:13:22,528
and very unnatural, but they are necessary.

290
00:13:23,429 --> 00:13:25,890
I like to start by not giving much direction at first

291
00:13:26,030 --> 00:13:27,370
and start restricting from there.

292
00:13:28,550 --> 00:13:30,271
Getting an accurate data on the stage

293
00:13:30,351 --> 00:13:32,472
will save a lot of animator time.

294
00:13:33,312 --> 00:13:34,953
You will need to find the right balance

295
00:13:35,053 --> 00:13:36,653
between the time spent at the stage

296
00:13:36,793 --> 00:13:39,114
and time spent adjusting the animations.

297
00:13:40,112 --> 00:13:42,334
Here are a few tricks we use for gameplay captures.

298
00:13:42,934 --> 00:13:45,557
Guide on the ground to keep the actors on a straight line,

299
00:13:46,017 --> 00:13:48,059
cones to measure the speed, and guides

300
00:13:48,099 --> 00:13:50,480
to make sure the actors end up with the correct foot

301
00:13:50,521 --> 00:13:50,921
position.

302
00:13:52,342 --> 00:13:54,624
When capturing movements or scenes in parts,

303
00:13:55,144 --> 00:13:56,986
make sure you choose a good branching point.

304
00:13:57,686 --> 00:13:59,828
Match the poses and momentum, and make

305
00:13:59,868 --> 00:14:02,010
sure you have enough data so you can

306
00:14:02,050 --> 00:14:03,651
do a good blend between them.

307
00:14:05,593 --> 00:14:08,175
And finally, some tips to manipulate motion capture data.

308
00:14:09,688 --> 00:14:16,013
When assembling takes together, make sure you spend time on assembling face before committing to polish.

309
00:14:16,694 --> 00:14:19,216
Avoid foot sliding big lerps or pops.

310
00:14:19,917 --> 00:14:23,560
Ideally, if something wasn't capturing properly, you would recapture it.

311
00:14:23,960 --> 00:14:29,345
But if you can't, try to do your best while working in non-linear editing, such as tracks or time editor.

312
00:14:30,967 --> 00:14:33,468
When a designer asks you to make an animation faster,

313
00:14:33,808 --> 00:14:37,050
doesn't mean make it faster, just mean make it shorter.

314
00:14:37,730 --> 00:14:39,811
So instead of speeding up the animation as a whole,

315
00:14:40,171 --> 00:14:42,972
you could try to make just some of those parts shorter.

316
00:14:44,193 --> 00:14:45,273
For this, I use a trick,

317
00:14:45,473 --> 00:14:47,374
which is blending the animation with itself

318
00:14:47,714 --> 00:14:48,915
in tracks or time editor.

319
00:14:49,745 --> 00:14:53,366
I look at the original data and analyze where it would be okay to collapse time.

320
00:14:53,946 --> 00:14:57,767
Places like struggles, long recoveries, settlings, anticipations.

321
00:14:58,527 --> 00:15:02,748
These methods allowed for a very fast iteration without losing data and it's a very, very

322
00:15:02,788 --> 00:15:03,389
visual way.

