00:21:51,192 --> 00:21:53,853
Second tip, double-up on controllers to avoid gimbal lock.

470
00:21:54,453 --> 00:21:56,013
All right, so if you're an animator like me,

471
00:21:56,073 --> 00:21:58,434
then you love doing animations full of flips and spins.

472
00:21:58,534 --> 00:22:01,015
However, if you're only using one controller to do this,

473
00:22:01,115 --> 00:22:03,016
then you might notice something a little bit unnatural.

474
00:22:03,436 --> 00:22:04,597
And this is because of gimbal lock,

475
00:22:04,837 --> 00:22:07,258
which gives priority to an axis while rotating an object.

476
00:22:07,758 --> 00:22:09,859
If you're having gimbal lock issues during flips and spins

477
00:22:09,939 --> 00:22:11,559
and you can't send it back to a rigger to fix it,

478
00:22:11,819 --> 00:22:13,280
such as during an animation test,

479
00:22:13,620 --> 00:22:15,281
well then, you might wanna try out this simple trick.

480
00:22:16,001 --> 00:22:18,962
Create a new noob circle and scale it so you can easily see it around your character.

481
00:22:19,562 --> 00:22:22,823
Then parent the original master controller to the new controller you just created.

482
00:22:23,783 --> 00:22:26,584
Use one controller for all the flips and the other controller for all the spins.

483
00:22:27,184 --> 00:22:30,726
Because you're dedicating each controller to rotate in only one direction, gimbal locks

484
00:22:30,746 --> 00:22:35,227
shouldn't be a problem anymore and you can go about making your sweet animation.

