00:23:13,235 --> 00:23:17,740
This lessens your anxiety and shows that you were thinking of how to do the attack with an enemy in mind the whole time.

498
00:23:19,175 --> 00:23:20,716
Four, twinning the correct way.

499
00:23:21,356 --> 00:23:22,437
No, I'm not talking about twins here.

500
00:23:22,477 --> 00:23:24,638
I'm talking about when two objects move in parallel

501
00:23:24,738 --> 00:23:25,459
at the same time.

502
00:23:25,819 --> 00:23:27,220
Thank you, Mr. Obama, for demonstrating.

503
00:23:27,760 --> 00:23:29,001
If you're an animator, new or old,

504
00:23:29,061 --> 00:23:31,282
then you've probably heard that twinning is bad.

505
00:23:31,403 --> 00:23:33,024
However, I'm here to tell you it isn't,

506
00:23:33,164 --> 00:23:34,284
as long as you do it correctly.

507
00:23:34,665 --> 00:23:36,446
Tim Ritter goes into this concept more in depth,

508
00:23:36,486 --> 00:23:38,927
but let me reiterate that if you're twinning, that's okay.

509
00:23:39,007 --> 00:23:40,789
Just make sure that you're breaking up the animation

510
00:23:40,809 --> 00:23:41,429
to account for it.

511
00:23:42,547 --> 00:23:44,629
Space your timing so that the poses land at separate times,

512
00:23:45,029 --> 00:23:46,531
lead the motions into different directions,

513
00:23:46,951 --> 00:23:48,052
offset one part of the body

514
00:23:48,212 --> 00:23:50,615
so that it makes the character less symmetrical,

515
00:23:51,055 --> 00:23:53,157
avoid consecutive twinning poses throughout the shot,

516
00:23:53,538 --> 00:23:54,919
and be intentional with your movements.

517
00:23:56,040 --> 00:23:58,162
Many successful games and animations in movies

518
00:23:58,202 --> 00:23:59,163
have done this successfully,

519
00:23:59,564 --> 00:24:00,405
so you'll be in good hands

520
00:24:00,425 --> 00:24:01,386
when you're trying it out for yourself.

521
00:24:02,791 --> 00:24:05,533
And also, and lastly, don't commit until you're ready.

522
00:24:05,974 --> 00:24:07,054
This isn't marriage advice,

523
00:24:07,094 --> 00:24:09,296
this is advice on when you should start a test.

524
00:24:09,957 --> 00:24:11,618
If you're currently in the middle of finals week,

525
00:24:11,718 --> 00:24:12,679
if you're crunching at work,

526
00:24:12,799 --> 00:24:15,180
or if things just feel a little bit more hectic than usual,

527
00:24:15,521 --> 00:24:16,862
don't start an animation test.

528
00:24:17,582 --> 00:24:18,843
Companies will often send you a test

529
00:24:18,863 --> 00:24:20,545
and give you an allotted amount of time to do it.

530
00:24:20,865 --> 00:24:22,806
However, they're usually pretty flexible

531
00:24:22,846 --> 00:24:24,367
about when you could start the test itself.

532
00:24:25,168 --> 00:24:26,109
Take them up on their offer,

533
00:24:26,189 --> 00:24:27,630
and don't be afraid to say that you'd like

534
00:24:27,650 --> 00:24:29,531
to start the test a few days down the road.

535
00:24:30,343 --> 00:24:33,684
Also, if there are other candidates trying to take the test the same time as you, they're

536
00:24:33,704 --> 00:24:34,764
not going to pass you up in line.

537
00:24:35,124 --> 00:24:37,585
As long as your animation is good, that's what matters.

538
00:24:37,685 --> 00:24:41,166
And the only way you can make the animation the best it can be is if you have the time

539
00:24:41,386 --> 00:24:42,606
to commit to it fully.

540
00:24:43,546 --> 00:24:44,347
And that's my talk.

541
00:24:44,627 --> 00:24:47,387
Hopefully these tips will help you, as they have helped me.

542
00:24:47,868 --> 00:24:51,709
And if you didn't like it and you fell asleep throughout the presentation, well then hopefully

543
00:24:51,729 --> 00:24:53,589
I've at least assisted you in a five minute nap.

544
00:24:54,069 --> 00:24:54,269
All right.

545
00:24:54,309 --> 00:24:55,450
Lastly is Gwyn Frey.

546
00:24:55,470 --> 00:24:55,770
Thank you.

547
00:25:00,047 --> 00:25:01,288
There is one rule.

548
00:25:01,308 --> 00:25:06,092
All right.

549
00:25:06,252 --> 00:25:06,952
My name is Gwen.

550
00:25:07,232 --> 00:25:08,293
I am a technical animator.

551
00:25:08,453 --> 00:25:10,795
I am a studio founder for the Molasses Flood,

552
00:25:11,015 --> 00:25:12,636
and I'm the sole animator there.

553
00:25:12,997 --> 00:25:14,097
I'm going to showcase tips and tricks

554
00:25:14,117 --> 00:25:16,679
I used while working on this character, Scout.

555
00:25:16,719 --> 00:25:19,181
She's a prototype character we had in game.

556
00:25:19,361 --> 00:25:21,403
Or she's just a prototype character we had.

557
00:25:22,143 --> 00:25:23,264
When I started out with her, I wanted

558
00:25:23,284 --> 00:25:25,065
to make a character that had absolutely no transition

559
00:25:25,085 --> 00:25:25,806
animations at all.

560
00:25:26,196 --> 00:25:29,819
A transition animation is an animation that takes you from one loop, like a run or a walk,

561
00:25:29,859 --> 00:25:31,100
to another loop, like an idle.

562
00:25:31,500 --> 00:25:34,403
It tends to slow down your iteration because you have to update it every time you update

563
00:25:34,423 --> 00:25:34,903
either loop.

564
00:25:35,324 --> 00:25:38,326
Instead, for her, she has four animations total for her locomotion.

565
00:25:38,746 --> 00:25:42,549
An idle, a run, a walk, and a kind of hard stop animation.

566
00:25:43,530 --> 00:25:46,613
If you look at this video, you'll see that the moment Scout stops moving, the foot she

567
00:25:46,633 --> 00:25:48,534
has planted on the ground still stays on the ground.

568
00:25:48,875 --> 00:25:52,257
The foot that's in the air plants, and she'll shift her weight onto the newly planted foot,

569
00:25:52,338 --> 00:25:54,139
and then slide the foot that's on the ground.

570
00:25:54,512 --> 00:25:56,553
to match where it needs to be for the idle location.

571
00:25:57,213 --> 00:25:59,314
The way I did this is I made two float tracks

572
00:25:59,414 --> 00:26:02,276
in the walk and the run cycles.

573
00:26:03,476 --> 00:26:04,697
One float track is for the left foot

574
00:26:04,737 --> 00:26:05,757
and one is for the right foot.

575
00:26:06,078 --> 00:26:08,679
And they'll blend from one when the foot

576
00:26:08,719 --> 00:26:10,980
is planted on the ground to zero when the foot is in the air.

577
00:26:11,640 --> 00:26:13,181
Whenever the scout stops moving,

578
00:26:13,241 --> 00:26:14,782
I freeze her locomotion animation

579
00:26:14,822 --> 00:26:16,122
and I can query these two tracks

580
00:26:16,182 --> 00:26:18,043
to see if a foot is planted on the ground or not.

581
00:26:19,344 --> 00:26:21,505
I also added a remain planted float track

582
00:26:21,545 --> 00:26:22,705
to the hard stop animation.

583
00:26:23,109 --> 00:26:25,150
This track is one for the first half of the animation

584
00:26:25,251 --> 00:26:27,252
and blends to zero over the time I wanted to move

585
00:26:27,292 --> 00:26:29,493
her planted foot to the idle location.

586
00:26:30,014 --> 00:26:33,136
Now all I have to do is multiply that is planted float track

587
00:26:33,296 --> 00:26:35,438
for each foot by the remain planted track

588
00:26:35,458 --> 00:26:36,558
in the hard stop animation.

589
00:26:36,979 --> 00:26:39,580
And I can use that to drive the blend

590
00:26:39,640 --> 00:26:41,001
for the IK target bones.

591
00:26:41,702 --> 00:26:43,243
I just said I'm using IK target bones,

592
00:26:43,263 --> 00:26:44,284
let's talk about IK.

593
00:26:45,084 --> 00:26:46,705
This strategy requires that I have IK running

594
00:26:46,725 --> 00:26:47,726
on my character at all times.

595
00:26:47,786 --> 00:26:48,927
This is pretty typical for me.

596
00:26:48,967 --> 00:26:51,068
And I tend to set up IK in a similar fashion

597
00:26:51,108 --> 00:26:52,109
for all of my characters.

598
00:26:53,220 --> 00:26:55,322
I have bones in the rig for the leg IK targets.

599
00:26:55,582 --> 00:26:57,443
These bones are constrained to the ankle bones

600
00:26:57,503 --> 00:26:59,204
but parented under the root of the character.

601
00:26:59,805 --> 00:27:00,706
Since these are in the rig,

602
00:27:00,746 --> 00:27:02,787
they're automatically exported for every animation I make.

603
00:27:02,907 --> 00:27:05,209
So anytime in engine I need to figure out

604
00:27:05,229 --> 00:27:06,930
where the feet should be in root relative space,

605
00:27:06,990 --> 00:27:08,871
I can just query the location of these bones.

606
00:27:10,212 --> 00:27:12,253
I also have bones parented under the pole vectors

607
00:27:12,273 --> 00:27:12,974
for the leg IK.

608
00:27:13,034 --> 00:27:14,275
I figure we're, as animators,

609
00:27:14,295 --> 00:27:15,576
we're already managing the pole vector.

610
00:27:15,616 --> 00:27:17,957
We might as well bring that information into the game,

611
00:27:18,338 --> 00:27:20,899
into the engine, and use that to drive our pole vectors

612
00:27:21,039 --> 00:27:22,240
for the in-game IK as well.

613
00:27:23,882 --> 00:27:26,344
I use IK for run stop, but I use it for all kinds of other things as well.

614
00:27:26,424 --> 00:27:30,026
Here I'm using it to make a quick and dirty kind of slope variation for all of our locomotion.

615
00:27:30,466 --> 00:27:34,748
All I did here was I took the IK target bones, parented them under a world orientation bone,

616
00:27:35,148 --> 00:27:39,010
and every tick I cast a ray down to the world and find the normal angle of the world to

617
00:27:39,050 --> 00:27:40,291
set the orientation of this bone.

618
00:27:40,731 --> 00:27:45,334
This will obviously orient the IK feet to the ground.

619
00:27:45,954 --> 00:27:50,417
You'll notice if you're watching here very carefully that as her feet approach the ground,

620
00:27:50,517 --> 00:27:53,718
they blend into the IK and they blend out whenever she takes her feet off of the ground.

621
00:27:54,173 --> 00:27:55,873
Also, whenever she's jumping, for instance,

622
00:27:56,254 --> 00:27:57,414
in-game IK will turn off.

623
00:27:58,014 --> 00:27:58,975
Guess how I'm doing that?

624
00:27:59,415 --> 00:28:01,095
I'm exporting that from Maya as well.

625
00:28:01,496 --> 00:28:05,757
So I actually export the blend between IK and FK in Maya,

626
00:28:05,957 --> 00:28:09,338
and I have that float track drive the in-game IK in Engine.

627
00:28:09,759 --> 00:28:13,040
What this means is, when I'm animating something

628
00:28:13,060 --> 00:28:15,121
like this jump here, I'm thinking,

629
00:28:15,461 --> 00:28:17,942
as I blend from FK to IK, that

630
00:28:18,318 --> 00:28:22,820
her feet in IK might be slightly manipulated by slope variation or something else in game.

631
00:28:22,920 --> 00:28:24,500
I just keep that in mind as I animate.

632
00:28:27,401 --> 00:28:30,843
Speaking of jumps, for a traditional jump, you have a looping fall animation,

633
00:28:30,903 --> 00:28:34,124
and then you kind of hit the ground and you blend really quickly into this landing animation.

634
00:28:34,464 --> 00:28:36,665
You don't have a lot of frames to play with if you do that.

635
00:28:36,705 --> 00:28:38,466
You can't really give the character a lot of weight.

636
00:28:38,966 --> 00:28:40,467
I generally think this kind of looks bad.

637
00:28:40,927 --> 00:28:44,648
I saw a talk that Loren did for Paragon, and I kind of stole his idea.

638
00:28:45,544 --> 00:28:48,206
Instead, I animate the land from a much higher point off of the ground,

639
00:28:48,246 --> 00:28:50,528
and I have her feet reach through the collision cylinder

640
00:28:50,568 --> 00:28:54,090
and touch the ground before she actually makes contact with the ground.

641
00:28:55,111 --> 00:28:56,412
I don't actually play this animation.

642
00:28:56,772 --> 00:28:59,454
What I do is I query the distance she is from the ground,

643
00:28:59,854 --> 00:29:02,056
and I use that to select a frame of this animation.

644
00:29:03,117 --> 00:29:05,819
So, to reiterate, that animation happened,

645
00:29:06,139 --> 00:29:08,120
it started with her 100 units off of the ground.

646
00:29:08,641 --> 00:29:11,103
So, in Engine, what I'm doing is I'm detecting

647
00:29:11,963 --> 00:29:13,724
how far she's off of the ground, dividing that by 100.

648
00:29:14,532 --> 00:29:16,093
and playing the frame that is that percentage

649
00:29:16,133 --> 00:29:16,953
through the animation.

650
00:29:17,293 --> 00:29:18,554
This animation does not play.

651
00:29:19,154 --> 00:29:21,416
I am selecting a frame of the animation

652
00:29:21,676 --> 00:29:24,377
based on an input variable, which is in this case,

653
00:29:24,418 --> 00:29:25,458
the distance from the ground.

654
00:29:25,998 --> 00:29:27,659
This is important because, like, say,

655
00:29:27,920 --> 00:29:29,380
she could be falling at different velocities,

656
00:29:29,681 --> 00:29:30,701
they could manipulate the arcs.

657
00:29:30,741 --> 00:29:32,062
It doesn't matter what the designer does,

658
00:29:32,182 --> 00:29:33,563
because the animation is data-driven,

659
00:29:33,863 --> 00:29:35,384
her feet will never penetrate through the ground.

660
00:29:36,024 --> 00:29:37,465
I use this concept for all kinds of things.

661
00:29:37,525 --> 00:29:39,907
For instance, I dislike how turn-and-place animations

662
00:29:39,947 --> 00:29:40,627
are usually set up.

663
00:29:41,067 --> 00:29:41,668
It's usually a lot of

664
00:29:42,287 --> 00:29:43,907
different footfall animations blending together

665
00:29:43,927 --> 00:29:44,788
in some kind of hot mess.

666
00:29:45,388 --> 00:29:47,488
Instead of that, what I did for her was

667
00:29:47,989 --> 00:29:49,369
I made one turn-in-place animation

668
00:29:49,849 --> 00:29:51,350
that turns her 360 degrees.

669
00:29:51,450 --> 00:29:53,511
And I queried the world space orientation

670
00:29:54,211 --> 00:29:55,431
of Scout at all times.

671
00:29:55,871 --> 00:29:58,652
And I used that orientation to drive the frame

672
00:29:58,672 --> 00:30:00,273
that I'm selecting of this animation.

673
00:30:00,833 --> 00:30:04,715
So for instance, as she's turning,

674
00:30:05,075 --> 00:30:07,476
and the engine detects that she's turning left or right,

675
00:30:08,376 --> 00:30:10,397
this animation will play forwards or backwards.

676
00:30:10,891 --> 00:30:13,052
I'm constantly selecting a frame of this animation

677
00:30:13,112 --> 00:30:14,592
based on her world space orientation.

678
00:30:14,892 --> 00:30:15,633
What you're seeing right here

679
00:30:15,673 --> 00:30:17,213
is actually only three animations.

680
00:30:17,733 --> 00:30:19,854
One where she has her feet moving,

681
00:30:20,094 --> 00:30:22,295
one where an identical animation to that,

682
00:30:22,715 --> 00:30:24,136
that just has her feet planted on the ground

683
00:30:24,176 --> 00:30:27,037
that I blend to anytime the world orientation

684
00:30:27,077 --> 00:30:27,737
is not changing.

685
00:30:28,157 --> 00:30:30,218
And then an additive idle that plays over the whole setup.

686
00:30:30,778 --> 00:30:31,818
So with three animations,

687
00:30:31,878 --> 00:30:35,400
I can actually make a pretty decent turn in place.

688
00:30:36,020 --> 00:30:37,120
All right, this has been.

689
00:30:38,069 --> 00:30:40,771
tricks of the trade. You may now everybody stand up.

690
00:30:54,979 --> 00:31:01,003
Thank you. We hit it perfectly and have no time for questions. Have a wonderful day.

